thoughts.a: The input and output grids are the same sizes. the input grid is a large grid of mostly pink background tiles but also contains squiggly paths of gray and of orange tiles. Initially, the squiggly orange and gray tile paths look like they are scattered at random. The output grid looks very similar to the input grid with the exception that a specific large sections of the pink background has now been changed to gray tiles. How do we know which specific large sections should be changed to gray and which tiles should be kept exactly the same? Looking back at the input grid, we notice that the squiggly paths are not actually random at all. Some of them certainly are, but some of them form a single continuous path of gray. We notice there are two longer, single gray paths and generally follow each others shapes, similar to a winding walkway within a park. Additionally, contained within this internal section of this walkway, are orange tile paths that help to better define the walkway structure by connected the two boundary edges of this walkway. Once this has been spotted and defined, then the output grid can simply be described as an exact copy of the input grid with the exception of filling in the walkway with the boundary tile color, which in this case is gray. The orange structure tiles are not change to gray, only the pink color background tiles that are contained within the boundaries of the walkway. Thus the hypothesis is the following. The input grid will contain some background color, probably pink. It will also contain two other non-background colors. One of these colors will have two long squiggly paths that look like that follow roughly the same shape and which will define the walkway. The other color will help to further define the structure of the walkway by connected the two sides of the boundaries of the walkway together periodically through the internal part of the walkway. In order to construct the output grid we need to copy over the input grid as is with the exception of filling in the walkway entirely with the color of the boundary. Note that the helpful interior structures do not change their colors in the output grid.
thoughts.b: The input grid is a large grid of mostly green background tiles. There are also squiggly yellow and black paths throughout the input grid. According to the hypothesis, in order to construct the output grid, we need to copy over the input grid as is with the exception of filling in the interior of the identified walkway with the same color as the boundary color of the walkway. In this case, the walkway starts in the top right and ends in the bottom left. We identify it by the two roughly same shaped yellow long paths that are helpfully better defined by repeated diagonal black lines that connect the two boundary edges together. The rest of the yellow and black tiles exterior are simply distraction tiles that are meant to obfuscate where the walkway is. Once we have identified the walkway, the output grid simply needs to fill in all the interior tiles of that walkway with yellow tiles, but the black tiles should stay in their same location and color in the output grid. Because this is exactly what we see in the output grid, the hypothesis holds.
thoughts.c: The input grid is a large grid of mostly aqua color background tiles. There are also squiggly purple and green paths throughout the input grid. According to the hypothesis, in order to construct the output grid, we need to copy over the input grid as is, with the exception of filling in the interior of the identified walkway with the same color as the boundary color of the walkway. In this case, the walkway starts in the left edge of the input grid and ends on the bottom edge of the input grid. We identify it by the two roughly same shaped purple paths that are helpfully better defined by the repeated green lines that connect these two boundary paths together to form the walkway. The rest of the green and purple tiles in the input grid are simply distraction tiles. Once we have identified the walkway, the output grid simply needs to fill in all of the interior tiles of that walkway with purple tiles. Note that the green helpful structure tiles stay in their same location and color in the output grid. Because this is exactly what we see in the output grid the hypothesis holds.
